event-driven systems. 
3. Significance of the for Loop with 4 Iterations
for i := 0; i < 4; i++
This loop creates 4 worker goroutines.
Each worker runs this code:
for f := range cnp {
    f()
}
Meaning:
Wait for a function from the channelExecute the function.
Continue waiting for more tasks.
This pattern is known as a worker pool.
Example:
Worker1 → executes task
Worker2 → executes task
Worker3 → executes task
Worker4 → executes task
Benefits:
controlled concurrency
better CPU utilization
avoids creating unlimited goroutines
4. Significance of make(chan func(), 10)
The channel has a buffer size of 10.
This means:
up to 10 tasks can wait in the queue
sending tasks will not block until the buffer is full
System capacity example:Workers running tasks: 4
Tasks waiting in queue: 10
This improves performance and throughput in concurrent systems.
5. Why “HERE1” is Not Getting Printed
The function is sent to the channel:
cnp <- func() {
    fmt.Println("HERE1")
}
However, the program immediately continues:
fmt.Println("Hello")
After printing "Hello", the main function exits.
When main() exits:
the program terminates
all goroutines stop immediately
So the worker goroutine may not get time to execute the function, and "HERE1" may never be printed.
Hello6. Fixing the Issue
The program must wait for the worker goroutines to finish executing tasks.
Example fix using sleep:
package main
import (
    "fmt"
    "time"
)

func main() {
    cnp := make(chan func(), 10)

    for i := 0; i < 4; i++ {
        go func() {
            for f := range cnp {
                f()
            }
        }()
    }

    cnp <- func() {
        fmt.Println("HERE1")
    }

    fmt.Println("Hello")

    time.Sleep(time.Second)
}
Expected output:Hello
HERE1
